From: Christian Walter <christian.walter@9elements.com>
Date: Sun, 16 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ikvm: add zero-copy XRGB32 framebuffer support

Add support for V4L2_PIX_FMT_XRGB32 pixel format and eliminate the
framebuffer copy for raw pixel formats.

For video capture devices that output raw 32-bit XRGB pixels (such as
the HPE GXP thumbnail video engine), the current code copies the entire
frame from the V4L2 mmap'd buffer into the VNC framebuffer vector via
std::vector::assign(). On a 1024x768 display at 32bpp, this is a 3 MB
memcpy per frame.

This patch eliminates that copy by pointing the VNC server's
frameBuffer pointer directly at the V4L2 mmap'd buffer. This is safe
because:

1. The obmc-ikvm manager uses lock-step thread synchronization: the
   video thread and server thread never access the framebuffer
   concurrently. sendFrame() runs in the video phase, and
   rfbProcessEvents() (which reads the framebuffer for encoding)
   runs in the server phase after sendFrame() returns.

2. The V4L2 buffer lifecycle already supports this: getFrame() holds
   one buffer (lastFrameIndex) out of the driver queue while the
   other buffers are re-queued. The held buffer remains valid until
   the next getFrame() call, which only happens after the server
   thread completes.

3. Modern VNC clients use CursorShapeUpdates, so libvncserver sends
   cursor shape via the protocol rather than drawing into the
   framebuffer.

The JPEG path is unaffected - it already achieves zero-copy via
rfbSendCompressedDataTight().

Upstream-Status: Pending
Signed-off-by: Christian Walter <christian.walter@9elements.com>
---
 ikvm_server.cpp | 12 ++++++++++++
 ikvm_video.cpp  |  3 ++-
 2 files changed, 14 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/ikvm_server.cpp b/ikvm_server.cpp
index 9274a9b..5306d04 100644
--- a/ikvm_server.cpp
+++ b/ikvm_server.cpp
@@ -159,6 +159,18 @@ void Server::sendFrame()
 
         switch (video.getPixelformat())
         {
+            case V4L2_PIX_FMT_XRGB32:
+                /*
+                 * Zero-copy: point VNC framebuffer directly at the V4L2
+                 * mmap'd buffer instead of copying via assign().
+                 *
+                 * Safe due to lock-step threading in Manager::run() and
+                 * the hold-one-buffer pattern in Video::getFrame().
+                 */
+                server->frameBuffer = data;
+                rfbMarkRectAsModified(server, 0, 0, video.getWidth(),
+                                      video.getHeight());
+                break;
             case V4L2_PIX_FMT_RGB24:
                 framebuffer.assign(data, data + video.getFrameSize());
                 rfbMarkRectAsModified(server, 0, 0, video.getWidth(),
diff --git a/ikvm_video.cpp b/ikvm_video.cpp
index 3445715..2f637d6 100644
--- a/ikvm_video.cpp
+++ b/ikvm_video.cpp
@@ -459,7 +459,8 @@ void Video::start()
     width = fmt.fmt.pix.width;
     pixelformat = fmt.fmt.pix.pixelformat;
 
-    if (pixelformat != V4L2_PIX_FMT_RGB24 && pixelformat != V4L2_PIX_FMT_JPEG)
+    if (pixelformat != V4L2_PIX_FMT_RGB24 && pixelformat != V4L2_PIX_FMT_JPEG
+        && pixelformat != V4L2_PIX_FMT_XRGB32)
     {
         log<level::ERR>("Pixel Format not supported",
                         entry("PIXELFORMAT=%d", pixelformat));
